The paper deals with concurrent programming and algorithms for snapshot implementations, which are typically studied in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses the linearizability condition, which is a fundamental concept in programming language theory and verification, making the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category a likely fit. The paper also involves the use of mathematical functions and simple executions, which are common topics in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-categories. Finally, the paper mentions the potential for automatic verification of snapshot algorithms, which falls under the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category.
